                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 5315/813.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Ambassador <persName type="from">Bacon</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase—Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1910-03-02">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 2, 1910</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Mr. Bacon states that the foreign office has not yet received a reply from
                    England, but in answer to his specific question said that he might inform his
                    Government that France would be perfectly <pb facs="0386" n="274"
                        xml:id="pg_274"/> satisfied to accept proposition to concede to France 100
                    kilometers Ch’eng-tu extension, England to satisfy them as to subengineer
                    Hankow-Canton, France to have westernmost division of Ch’eng-tu extension.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
